Week 4 Natural Language Processing¶

Step 1 Description of the the problem and Data¶

The data comes from a Kaggle competition. This came directly from their competition website https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/nlp-getting-started/overview

Competition Description Twitter has become an important communication channel in times of emergency.

The ubiquitousness of smartphones enables people to announce an emergency theyre observing in real-time. Because of this, more agencies are interested in programatically monitoring Twitter (i.e. disaster relief organizations and news agencies).

But, its not always clear whether a persons words are actually announcing a disaster. Take this example:

The author explicitly uses the word ABLAZE but means it metaphorically. This is clear to a human right away, especially with the visual aid. But its less clear to a machine.

In this competition, youre challenged to build a machine learning model that predicts which Tweets are about real disasters and which ones arent. Youll have access to a dataset of 10,000 tweets that were hand classified. If this is your first time working on an NLP problem, we've created a quick tutorial to get you up and running.

Disclaimer: The dataset for this competition contains text that may be considered profane, vulgar, or offensive.

The training dataset consists of 7503 tweets and 222 unique words within those tweets. The testing dataset consists of 3243 tweets and 222 unique words within thouse tweets.

The training dataset has an extra column called target which is the designation of if it was a disaster tweet or a non-disaster tweet.

Now we will get started on the project by declaring some of the python libraries as well as downloading a list of stop words typically used.

Word Frequency¶

It's vitally important to look at the distribution of words used in diaster vs non-disaster tweets.

In [121]:
def clean_text(text):
    text = text.lower()
    text = re.sub(r"http\S+", "", text)  # remove links
    text = re.sub(r"[^a-zA-Z\s]", "", text)
    return text

df['text_clean'] = df['text'].apply(clean_text)

stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))

def get_top_n_words(corpus, n=None):
    vec = CountVectorizer(stop_words='english').fit(corpus)
    bag_of_words = vec.transform(corpus)
    sum_words = bag_of_words.sum(axis=0)
    words_freq = [(word, sum_words[0, idx]) for word, idx in vec.vocabulary_.items()]
    words_freq = sorted(words_freq, key = lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    return pd.DataFrame(words_freq[:n], columns=['word', 'count'])

Word Cloud!¶

This shows the word clouds for both the disaster tweets as well as the non-disaster tweets. Word clouds simply show frequency of words by size. The larger the size of the word, the more frequent the word is within the group.

In [122]:
def show_wordcloud(text, title=None):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(
        background_color='white',
        stopwords=stop_words,
        max_words=200,
        max_font_size=40, 
        scale=3,
        random_state=1
    ).generate(str(text))

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
    plt.axis('off')
    if title:
        plt.title(title, fontsize=16)
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
    plt.show()

show_wordcloud(df[df.target==1]['text_clean'], "WordCloud - Disaster Tweets")
show_wordcloud(df[df.target==0]['text_clean'], "WordCloud - Non-Disaster Tweets")

For diaster you can see top words such as earthquakes, fire, etc while for the non-disaster tweets you see things like car, love, fast etc. Reasonably, the contents of the tweets appear appropriate for within our group designations.

Get the Bigram and Trigrams for each group¶

This EDA looks at the top words that are paired and 3-word matches in the tweets.

In [123]:
def get_ngrams(corpus, ngram_range=(2,2), top_n=15):
    vec = CountVectorizer(ngram_range=ngram_range, stop_words='english').fit(corpus)
    bag = vec.transform(corpus)
    sum_words = bag.sum(axis=0)
    ngrams_freq = [(word, sum_words[0, idx]) for word, idx in vec.vocabulary_.items()]
    ngrams_freq = sorted(ngrams_freq, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    return ngrams_freq[:top_n]

print("Top 15 Bigrams:")
print(get_ngrams(df['text_clean'], (2,2)))

print("Top 15 Trigrams:")
print(get_ngrams(df['text_clean'], (3,3)))

View Hashtags and mentions¶

Hashtags and mentions are important in tweets since they are used to enhance discoverability and facilitate conversation/participation. For disaster related tweets, if a group of tweets all have the same hashtag then it becomes more popular and focused globally. We would expect this phenomena to happen during disaster tweets where a group of tweets contribute to the news. On the other hand, we would expect more randomized hashtags/mentions for non-disaster tweets.

In [124]:
# Extract hashtags and mentions
def extract_hashtags(text):
    return re.findall(r"#(\w+)", text)

def extract_mentions(text):
    return re.findall(r"@(\w+)", text)

df['hashtags'] = df['text'].apply(extract_hashtags)
df['mentions'] = df['text'].apply(extract_mentions)

# Flatten helper
def flatten_lists(series):
    return sum(series, [])

# Count top N
def get_top_counts(items, top_n=15):
    return pd.DataFrame(Counter(items).most_common(top_n), columns=['item', 'count'])

# Visualize
def plot_top_items(df_items, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    sns.barplot(data=df_items, y='item', x='count')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel("Frequency")
    plt.ylabel("Item")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()


# Getting the Top Hashtags
hashtags_all = flatten_lists(df['hashtags'])
hashtags_dis = flatten_lists(df[df.target==1]['hashtags'])
hashtags_non = flatten_lists(df[df.target==0]['hashtags'])

plot_top_items(get_top_counts(hashtags_all), "Hashtags (All Tweets)")
plot_top_items(get_top_counts(hashtags_dis), "Hashtags (Disaster Tweets)")
plot_top_items(get_top_counts(hashtags_non), "Hashtags (Non-Disaster Tweets)")

# Getting the top Mentions

For the hashtags, we can see an overabundance of the words News and news in the disaster tweets. This makes sense because you would expect the word news to be used to describe something happening that is fairly important. News organizations such as FoxNews, AP, usatoday, reuters are on the disaster list which reflects reporting events. Keeping in mind though that news can be used in different ways you can see that news is also on the non-disaster tweet list.

Mentions are more clearly defined within the disaster categories. The top disaster mentions are YouTube, FoxNews, and POTUS which would clearly indicate major evenst occurring. The non-disaster tweets are mentioning YouTube as well, but notice that things like ArianaGrande and justinbieber are on that list. So, ultimately I think the mentions are reflecting a clear definition between the diaster and non-disaster tweets.

Final preprocessing step¶

This is going to the final cleaning step from which the text will be passed into further evaluated models

In [125]:
# Preprocessing function
def clean_text(text):
    text = text.lower()
    text = re.sub(r"http\S+", "", text)
    text = re.sub(r"[^a-zA-Z\s]", "", text)
    text = re.sub(r"\s+", " ", text).strip()
    stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
    text = " ".join([word for word in text.split() if word not in stop_words])
    return text

train_df['text_clean'] = train_df['text'].apply(clean_text)
test_df['text_clean'] = test_df['text'].apply(clean_text)

Logistic regression¶

This is just a simple logistic regression supervised model to get a proper baseline for which to compare our LSTM model. Start with the TF-IDF vectorizer and feed that into the logistic regression model.

In [126]:

In [127]:
# Train/Test split for validation
X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.1, random_state=42)

# Model training
model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Validation evaluation

Here we can see the overall accuracy topping out at about 78%. Not terrible, but there is definite room for improvement. The precision/recall rates were a bit all over the place with 83% precision but only 64% recall in the non-disaster group, and a pretty good 90% recall rate in the disaster tweet group. So the logistic regression model is better at finding the real disaster tweets, but not great at classifying non-disaster tweets. Ultimately, it is overclassifiying disaster tweets.

Second deep model using a LSTM text Classifier¶

Since the coursework for this week focused on the LSTM model definition, I thought I'd go ahead and get a little practice with the LSTM model applying it to this dataset.

In [129]:
train_df['text_clean'] = train_df['text'].apply(clean_text)
test_df['text_clean'] = test_df['text'].apply(clean_text)

# Tokenization
tokenizer = Tokenizer(num_words=10000, oov_token="<OOV>")
tokenizer.fit_on_texts(train_df['text_clean'])

# Convert text to sequences
X = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(train_df['text_clean'])
X = pad_sequences(X, padding='post', maxlen=100)
X_test = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(test_df['text_clean'])
X_test = pad_sequences(X_test, padding='post', maxlen=100)

y = train_df['target'].values

# Train/test split
X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.1, random_state=42)

# LSTM Model
model = Sequential([
    Embedding(input_dim=10000, output_dim=128, input_length=100),
    LSTM(64, return_sequences=False),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(32, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.3),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

# Train model
model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=5, batch_size=32, validation_data=(X_val, y_val))

# Evaluation
val_preds = (model.predict(X_val) > 0.5).astype("int32")
print(classification_report(y_val, val_preds))

Attempting now to use a bidirectional model instead of the sequential model...¶

I tried multiple types of LSTM models, but the bi-directional model performed the best. The next code block defines the model and uses class weights. If you don't use class weights, the model doesn't work at all and you do not classify a single non-disaster tweet. Code is a bit messy and all over the place. Many version incompatibilities between tensorflow and keras. This worked though setting some environmental variables.

The model looks like this :

In [131]:
# LSTM MODEL IS NOW BI-DIRECTIONAL!
model = Sequential([
    Embedding(input_dim=10000, output_dim=128, input_length=100),
    Bidirectional(LSTM(64, return_sequences=False)),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(32, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.3),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

# Train model
model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=5, batch_size=32, validation_data=(X_val, y_val))

# Evaluation
val_preds = (model.predict(X_val) > 0.5).astype("int32")
print(classification_report(y_val, val_preds))

Second attempt at LSTM model with using class weights and a bidirectional LSTM model.¶

Extended tweaking of the model using class weights. Class weights tell the model to care more about certain classes by scaling their contribution to the overall loss function. This can be helpful in situations where you have some class imbalance happening. Since we had an absoulte 0 for the non-disaster tweets group I wanted to implement class weights to force the model to care more about the non-disater tweets. The idea being that

from tensorflow.keras.layers import Embedding, LSTM, Dense, Dropout, Bidirectional
from sklearn.utils.class_weight import compute_class_weight


import os
os.environ['TF_CPP_MIN_LOG_LEVEL'] = '3'  # optional, hides noisy logs
os.environ['TF_FORCE_GPU_ALLOW_GROWTH'] = 'true'

# Clear all the graphs to avoid duplication
tf.keras.backend.clear_session()

# Compute class weights
class_weights = compute_class_weight(class_weight='balanced', classes=np.unique(y_train), y=y_train)
class_weight_dict = {0: class_weights[0], 1: class_weights[1]}
print(f"Class weights: {class_weight_dict}")

def build_model():
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Embedding(input_dim=10000, output_dim=128, input_length=100),
        tf.keras.layers.Bidirectional(tf.keras.layers.LSTM(64)),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(32, activation='relu'),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

model = build_model()

Step 4 Results and Analysis¶

The initial versions of the LSTM model performed very poorly. In fact, the first model that I put in there didn't even look at the second group and ignored the first.

Second implemenation of the LSTM model included the introduction of adding class weights to the model in order to force it to look at the non-disaster group of tweets.

Third implementation of the LSTM model made it a bidirectional model. The rationale for this is that in the bidirectional form of the LSTM, the input flows both ways and it's capable of utilizing information from both sides. In addition, the bidirectional model can be used to model sequential dependencies between words and phrases from both sides so it becomes a more powerful LSTM than the normal variety. Indeed, accuracy/precision/recall rates went from 57% to 78% which is close to where the logistic regresssion model was performing.

Here is the accuracy table for each of the attempts :

Something to notice about the accuracy table is that the seuqential LSTM performed the worst, but the LSTM models never reached the accuracy of the logistic regression model. It came close, but didn't quite reach it.

Here is the precision rates for each of the attempts :

Interestingly for precision we had a complete 0 for non-disaster tweets in the sequential LSTM. The disaster tweets did ok looking at the LSTM in the disaster, but the 0.83 precision for logistic regression is pretty high.

Here are the recall rates for each of the models :

Flipped from preicsion the 0.90 recall rate for logistic regression is the highest besides a complete 1.0 for the sequential LSTM. We already know that the sequential LSTM model is not working properly so we can ignore that. The 0.77 and 0.74 values for the bi-directional models are in alignment with each other for both the disaster and non-disaster groups. The class weight bi-directional model performed the highest recall rate for non-disaster tweets.

here are the f-1 score values for each of the models :

For the f-1 score we see that again there is some similarity between the bi-directional LSTM models and the logistic regression performed the best. Judging by all the metrics it's really about what you're most interested in. The bi-directional LSTM model seemed to be the most consistent across all the comparisons between groups when taking into account the accuracy/precision/recall/f1 score values. When adding in the class weights the recall rate improved from 0.70 to 0.75 in the non-disaster tweets. So ultimately the best model that we tested out for this simple dataset was the class weighted bi-direcitonal LSTM model.

However, it is worth noting that the logistic regression while having some swings in the precision/recall rates, that appeared to be a bit more accurate than the LSTM model. This is not surprising since logistic regression generally does better on short sparse and well separated text data. The LSTM models are better developed for long range dependencies where the text can make a generalized statement. Tweets on the other hand are short and sometimes hard to model.

Consider the comparision between the 2 statements :

Sentence format : Rising flood waters are causing the roads to become undrivable.

Tweet : Tsunami incoming! #flood

The tokenizer logistic regression will look at the tweet and be able to understand it while the LSTM model is trying to put it in context. Tweets are limited in the amount of characters so everyones shortening of the sentence won't always be the same. Just some food for thought on model selection overall.
